{{infobox Museum |name= '''Balmoral Grist Mill Museum''' |image= Balmoral Mills, Nova Scotia.jpg |established= 1874 |location= [[Balmoral Mills]], [[Nova Scotia]]. |type = history museum |director = |curator = |visitors = |website = [https://balmoralgristmill.novascotia.ca/ balmoralgristmill.novascotia.ca] }}
The '''Balmoral Grist Mill Museum''' is a restored 1874 water powered [[grist mill]] located in [[Balmoral Mills]], [[Nova Scotia]]. The site includes a {{convert|1|km|mi}} walking trail along the ravine of Balmoral Brook. The mill is part of the [[Nova Scotia Museum]] system. It could be used to grind [[wheat]], [[oats]], and [[buckwheat]] into [[flour]] and [[meal]].<ref>[http://museum.gov.ns.ca/en/home/ourmuseums/default.aspx Nova Scotia Museums]{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090125041021/http://museum.gov.ns.ca/en/home/ourmuseums/default.aspx |date=2009-01-25 }}</ref>
==History== The mill was built in 1874 by Alexander McKay, the son of Scottish immigrants. He purchased the land for the mill for $12. He utilized a new technology for the time, the [[water turbine]], to drive four grindstones. When Alexander died in 1886, the mill passed to his son, Hugh.<ref name="reid">{{cite magazine|last=Reid|first=Mark Collin|title=Against the grain|magazine=[[Canada's History]]|date=April-May 2018|volume=98|issue=2|pages=64-65|issn=1920-9894}}</ref>
Hugh sold the mill 20 years later to Alexander McLean MacDonald. MacDonald passed the mill to his son Archie in 1940. In the 1950s, the mill, facing competition from larger modern mills, shut down.<ref name="reid" />
In 1964, the Sunrise Trail Museum in [[Tatamagouche]] began the process of restoring the mill, hiring the former owner, Archie MacDonald to run the mill. Due to financial constraints, the mill was sold to the Nova Scotia government in 1966. The government restored the mill and added an electric motor to drive the mill stones in place of the turbine that once provided power.<ref name="reid" />
