{{infobox military structure |name = Fort de Bois-d'Arcy |native_name = |partof =[[Fortifications of Paris in the 19th and 20th centuries|Fortifications of Paris]], [[Séré de Rivières system]] |location = [[Bois-d'Arcy, Yvelines]], France |image = Plan fortifications place de Paris.JPG |caption = German postcard of the fortifications of Paris with Bois-d'Arcy part of St. Cyr |map_type = France Île-de-France |map_size = |map_alt = |map_caption = |type = Fort |coordinates = {{coord|48.793238|2.031623|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} |code = |built = {{Start date|1874}} |builder = |materials = |height = |used = |demolished = |condition =Archives du Film du [[Centre national de la cinématographie|CNC]] |ownership =[[Minister of Culture (France)|Ministry of Culture]] |open_to_public = |controlledby = France |garrison = |current_commander = |commanders = |occupants = |battles = [[World War II]] |events = |image2 = |caption2 = }}
The '''Fort de Bois-d'Arcy''', also called the '''Batterie de Bois-d'Arcy''', is one of the forts constructed at the end of the 19th century to defend [[Paris]]. It is located in the commune of [[Bois-d'Arcy, Yvelines|Bois d'Arcy]] in the [[Yvelines]] département of France. The fort is located in the southern part of the town to the south of [[Route nationale 12]]. It is now the home of the French national film archives, the [[National Center of Cinematography and the moving image|Centre national de la cinématographie]].
==History== Built between 1874 and 1881, the fort was planned to reinforce the western fortifications of Paris. The southwestern forts were designed to cover the approach of a relieving army from the western portions of France. The Bois-d'Arcy fort protected the neighboring [[Fort de Saint-Cyr]], [[Versailles (city)|Versailles]] and the Camp de Satory, covering the Trappes valley and railway lines from [[Le Havre]] and [[Tours]].<ref name="arcy1">{{cite web | url=http://www.boisdarcy.fr/La-Batterie-de-Bois-d-Arcy.php | title=La Batterie de Bois d'Arcy | publisher=Mairie Bois de l'Arcy | accessdate=July 15, 2012 | author=Thiébaud, Eric | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331132903/http://www.boisdarcy.fr/La-Batterie-de-Bois-d-Arcy.php | archivedate=March 31, 2012 | df= }}</ref>
During World War II the fort was occupied by German forces. Before leaving, the Germans blew up the front of the fort in 1944.<ref name="arcy1"/>
==Film depository== During the 1960s the fort was placed at the disposal of the [[Minister of Culture (France)|Ministry of Culture]] and was used by the [[Centre national de la cinématographie]] from 1969 as a storage center for nitrate-based films. It has since been designated a depository for all French films and is involved in the digitization of movies for [[digital preservation]].<ref name="pajolec1">{{cite web | url=http://ipr.univ-paris1.fr/spip.php?article364 | title=lletins :: Bulletin n° 26 Les archives françaises du film à Bois d’Arcy | publisher=Institut Pierre Renouvin | accessdate=July 15, 2012 | author=Le Pajolec, Sébastien}}</ref> It is classed as a [[Monument historique]], designated on 15 February 1991.<ref name="merimee1">{{cite web | url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00087792 | title=Batterie de Bois d'Arcy | publisher=Ministère de la Culture et de la Communication | work=Merimee | accessdate=July 15, 2012}}</ref>
