{{About|William Carew Hazlitt the English bibliographer, editor and writer|other persons named Hazlitt|Hazlitt (name)}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}
{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}
'''William Carew Hazlitt''' (22 August 1834 – 8 September 1913<ref>''Who's Who 1914'', p. xxii</ref>), known professionally as '''W. Carew Hazlitt''', was an [[England|English]] lawyer, [[bibliographer]], editor and writer. He was the son of the barrister and registrar [[William Hazlitt (registrar)|William Hazlitt]], a grandson of the essayist and critic [[William Hazlitt]],{{sfn|Dictionary of National Biography}} and a great-grandson of the Unitarian minister and author [[William Hazlitt (Unitarian minister)|William Hazlitt]]. William Carew Hazlitt was educated at the [[Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood|Merchant Taylors' School]] and was called to the bar of the [[Inner Temple]] in 1861.

== Works ==
Among his many publications are a {{cite book|author=<!-- William Carew Hazlitt -->|title=Handbook to the Popular, Poetical and Dramatic Literature of Great Britain: From the Invention of Printing to the Restoration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jqkYAAAAIAAJ|year=1867|publisher=J.R. Smith}}, supplemented in 1876, 1882, 1887 and 1889, a General Index by J. G. Gray appearing in 1893. Hazlitt published further contributions to the subject in ''Bibliographical Collections and Notes on Early English Literature, Made During the Years 1893–1903'' (1903), and a ''Manual for the Collector and Amateur of Old English Plays ...'' (1892). He was also the chief editor of an edition of Warton's ''[[The History of English Poetry|History of English Poetry]]'' (1871) and compiled the ''Catalogue of the Huth Library'' (1880).

He also published ''Collections and Notes, 1867-1876'' (London: Reeves & Turner, 1876, containing detailed bibliographical entries on many early English printed books) followed by {{cite book|author=<!-- William Carew Hazlitt -->|title=Bibliographical Collections and Notes on Early English Literature 1474-1700: Second Supplement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AKDEngEACAAJ|year=1882|publisher=[[Bernard Quaritch|Quaritch]]}}.
His autobiography is {{cite book|author=<!-- William Carew Hazlitt -->|title=The Confessions of a Collector|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/41393/41393-h/41393-h.htm|year=1897}}.

In 1875, he published an edition of the works of [[Thomas Randolph (poet)|Thomas Randolph]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/stream/poeticalanddrama01randuoft/poeticalanddrama01randuoft_djvu.txt |website=archive.org |title=Poetical and Dramatic Works of Thomas Randolph of Trinity College, Cambridge |last=Hazlitt |first=W. Carey |publisher=Reeves and Turner |location=London |year=1875 |accessdate=30 December 2014 }}</ref>

He published {{cite book|author=<!-- William Carew Hazlitt -->|title=The History of the Venetian Republic: Her Rise, Her Greatness, and Her Civilization|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bu83AAAAcAAJ|year=1860|publisher=Smith}} and {{cite book|author=<!-- William Carew Hazlitt -->|title=Old Cookery Books and Ancient Cuisine|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/12293|year=1886}}.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Peacock, Mabel|authorlink=Mabel Peacock|title=Review of ''Old Cookery Books and Ancient Cuisine'' by H. Carew Hazlitt|journal=The Academy and Literature|date=24 July 1886|volume=30|issue=742|page=61|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=chi.79227477;view=1up;seq=55}}</ref>

Of great use, interest and delight to gardeners and collectors of herbals, etc. is his ''[[Gleanings in Old Garden Literature]]'', published by [[Elliot Stock]], London, 1887, in ''The Book-Lover's Library''. This book includes, in its final chapter, a ''Bibliography of Gardening Literature, 1603 - 1800, and of Herbals and Bee Culture''.

Compendious in scope and idiosyncratic in selection is his {{cite book|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/brands-popular-antiquities-of-great-britain-faiths-and-folklore-a-dictionary-of-national-beliefs-superstitions-and-popular-customs-past-and-current-with-their-classical-and-foreign-analogues-described-and-illustrated/oclc/647632425|title=A Dictionary of Faiths and Folk Lore:|first=|publisher=Reeves & Turner|year=1905|isbn=|location=|pages=|quote=|via=|author=<!-- William Carew Hazlitt -->}}, which preserves evidence of numerous folk customs now extinct.

